\section*{Preface: Why Rotation?}
In the O\texttimes I framework, we promote the traditional two-dimensional spacetime vector $(t, x)$ into the three-dimensional vantage slice $(\tau, t_x, x)$. This lifting introduces \emph{vantage tilt}, a geometric re-interpretation of relativistic effects. Rather than introducing contraction or dilation as distortions, we represent them as the results of rotated frames in 7D manifold subspaces.

\vspace{1em}
\textbf{Justification for rotation-based lifting:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item[\checkmark] Each observer aligns their local clock axis $t_x$ with their perceived proper time, yielding a tilt relative to the global manifold direction $\tau$.
  \item[\checkmark] Relativistic effects appear as \emph{projections} from a rotated coordinate system back onto the flat $(t, x)$ space.
  \item[\checkmark] Orthogonality between local time and space axes is preserved within each observer's lifted frame.
  \item[\checkmark] Using rotation for lifting avoids explicit contraction/dilation; these emerge naturally through cross-frame comparisons.
\end{itemize}

Thus, the \textbf{Lift--Lift--Rotate} procedure proceeds as follows:

\section*{Step 1: Lift $(t, x)$ into $(\tau, t_x, x)$}
We begin with an unprimed observer in frame $K$, at rest in the global manifold. The time component is lifted via:
\begin{equation}
